# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: webhooks-pattern
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] An *event* can be defined as "a significant change in state".
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] For example, when a consumer purchases a car, the car's state changes from "for sale" to "sold".
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] A car dealer's system architecture may treat this state change as an event whose occurrence can be made known to other applications within the architecture.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] From a formal perspective, what is produced, published, propagated, detected or consumed is a (typically asynchronous) message called the event notification, and not the event itself, which is the state change that triggered the message emission.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] However, the term *event* is often used metonymically to denote the notification message itself, which may lead to some confusion.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] This is due to Event-driven architectures often being designed atop **message-driven architectures**, where such a communication pattern requires one of the inputs to be text-only, the message, to differentiate how each communication should be handled.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] This architectural pattern may be applied by the design and implementation of applications and systems that transmit events among loosely coupled software components and services.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] An event-driven system typically consists of event emitters (or agents), event consumers (or sinks), and event channels.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] Emitters have the responsibility to detect, gather, and transfer events.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] An Event Emitter does not know the consumers of the event, it does not even know if a consumer exists, and in case it exists, it does not know how the event is used or further processed.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] Sinks have the responsibility of applying a reaction as soon as an event is presented.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] The reaction might or might not be completely provided by the sink itself.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] For instance, the sink might just have the responsibility to filter, transform and forward the event to another component or it might provide a self-contained reaction to such an event.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] Event channels are conduits in which events are transmitted from event emitters to event consumers.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] The knowledge of the correct distribution of events is exclusively present within the event channel.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] The physical implementation of event channels can be based on traditional components such as message-oriented middleware or point-to-point communication which might require a more appropriate transactional executive framework.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] Building systems around an event-driven architecture simplifies horizontal scalability in distributed computing models and makes them more resilient to failure.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] This is because application state can be copied across multiple parallel snapshots for high-availability.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] New events can be initiated anywhere, but more importantly propagate across the network of data stores updating each as they arrive.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] Adding extra nodes becomes trivial as well: you can simply take a copy of the application state, feed it a stream of events and run with it.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] Event-driven architecture can complement service-oriented architecture (SOA) because services can be activated by triggers fired on incoming events.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] This paradigm is particularly useful whenever the sink does not provide any self-contained executive.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] SOA 2.0 evolves the implications SOA and EDA architectures provide to a richer, more robust level by leveraging previously unknown causal relationships to form a new event pattern.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] This new business intelligence pattern triggers further autonomous human or automated processing that adds exponential value to the enterprise by injecting value-added information into the recognized pattern which could not have been achieved previously.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] Event driven architecture has two primary topologies.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] With “broker topology”, components broadcast events to the entire system without any orchestrator.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] This topology provides higher performance and scalability.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] With “mediator topology”, there is a central orchestrator which controls workflow of events.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] This topology provides better control and error handling capabilities.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] You can also use a hybrid model and combine these two topologies.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] There are different types of events in EDA, and opinions on their classification may vary.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] Domain events signify important occurrences within a specific business domain.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] These events are restricted to a bounded context and are vital for preserving business logic.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] Typically, domain events have lighter payloads, containing only the necessary information for processing.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] This is because event listeners are generally within the same service, where their requirements are more clearly understood.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] On the other hand, integration events serve to communicate changes across different bounded contexts.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] They are crucial for ensuring data consistency throughout the entire system.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] Integration events tend to have more complex payloads with additional attributes, as the needs of potential listeners can differ significantly.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] This often leads to a more thorough approach to communication, resulting in overcommunication to ensure that all relevant information is effectively shared.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] An event can be made of two parts, the event header and the event body also known as event payload.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] The event header might include information such as event name, time stamp for the event, and type of event.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] The event payload provides the details of the state change detected.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] An event body should not be confused with the pattern or the logic that may be applied in reaction to the occurrence of the event itself.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] This method involves including only keys or IDs, allowing consumers to fetch the required data from external data sources, such as databases.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] While this approach is less scalable and slower due to the need for database queries, it minimizes bandwidth usage and reduces coupling issues.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] These methods represent two ends of a spectrum rather than binary choices.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] Architects must carefully size the event payloads to meet the specific needs of event consumers.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] In event driven architectures, event evolution poses challenges, such as managing inconsistent event schemas across services and ensuring compatibility during gradual system updates.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] Event evolution strategies in event-driven architectures (EDA) can ensure that systems can handle changes to events without disruption.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] These strategies can include versioning events, such as semantic versioning or schema evolution, to maintain backward and forward compatibility.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] Adapters can translate events between old and new formats, ensuring consistent processing across components.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] These techniques can enable systems to evolve while remaining compatible and reliable in complex, distributed environments.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] The first logical layer is the event producer, which senses a fact and represents that fact as an event message.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] As an example, an event producer could be an email client, an E-commerce system, a monitoring agent or some type of physical sensor.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] Converting the data collected from such a diverse set of data sources to a single standardized form of data for evaluation is a significant task in the design and implementation of this first logical layer.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] However, considering that an event is a strongly declarative frame, any informational operations can be easily applied, thus eliminating the need for a high level of standardization.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] An event channel is a mechanism of propagating the information collected from an event generator to the event engine or sink.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] This could be a TCP/IP connection, or any type of an input file (flat, XML format, e-mail, etc.).
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] Several event channels can be opened at the same time.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] Usually, because the event processing engine has to process them in near real time, the event channels will be read asynchronously.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] The events are stored in a queue, waiting to be processed later by the event processing engine.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] The event processing engine is the logical layer responsible for identifying an event, and then selecting and executing the appropriate reaction.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] It can also trigger a number of assertions.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] For example, if the event that comes into the event processing engine is a product ID low in stock, this may trigger reactions such as “Order product ID” and “Notify personnel”.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] This is the logical layer where the consequences of the event are shown.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] This can be done in many different ways and forms; e.g., an email is sent to someone and an application may display some kind of warning on the screen.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] Depending on the level of automation provided by the sink (event processing engine) the downstream activity might not be required.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] There are three general styles of event processing: simple, stream, and complex.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] The three styles are often used together in a mature event-driven architecture.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] Simple event processing concerns events that are directly related to specific, measurable changes of condition.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] In simple event processing, a notable event happens which initiates downstream action(s).
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] Simple event processing is commonly used to drive the real-time flow of work, thereby reducing lag time and cost.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] For example, simple events can be created by a sensor detecting changes in tire pressures or ambient temperature.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] The car's tire incorrect pressure will generate a simple event from the sensor that will trigger a yellow light advising the driver about the state of a tire.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] In event stream processing (ESP), both ordinary and notable events happen.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] Ordinary events (orders, RFID transmissions) are screened for notability and streamed to information subscribers.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] Event stream processing is commonly used to drive the real-time flow of information in and around the enterprise, which enables in-time decision making.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] Complex event processing (CEP) allows patterns of simple and ordinary events to be considered to infer that a complex event has occurred.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] Complex event processing evaluates a confluence of events and then takes action.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] The events (notable or ordinary) may cross event types and occur over a long period of time.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] The event correlation may be causal, temporal, or spatial.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] CEP requires the employment of sophisticated event interpreters, event pattern definition and matching, and correlation techniques.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] CEP is commonly used to detect and respond to business anomalies, threats, and opportunities.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] Online event processing (OLEP) uses asynchronous distributed event logs to process complex events and manage persistent data.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] OLEP allows reliably composing related events of a complex scenario across heterogeneous systems.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] It thereby enables very flexible distribution patterns with high scalability and offers strong consistency.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] However, it cannot guarantee upper bounds on processing time.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] An event-driven architecture is extremely loosely coupled and well distributed.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] The great distribution of this architecture exists because an event can be almost anything and exist almost anywhere.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] The architecture is extremely loosely coupled because the event itself doesn't know about the consequences of its cause. e.g.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] If we have an alarm system that records information when the front door opens, the door itself doesn't know that the alarm system will add information when the door opens, just that the door has been opened.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] Event-driven architectures have loose coupling within space, time and synchronization, providing a scalable infrastructure for information exchange and distributed workflows.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] However, event-architectures are tightly coupled, via event subscriptions and patterns, to the semantics of the underlying event schema and values.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] The high degree of semantic heterogeneity of events in large and open deployments such as smart cities and the sensor web makes it difficult to develop and maintain event-based systems.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] In order to address semantic coupling within event-based systems the use of approximate semantic matching of events is an active area of research.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] Event driven architecture is susceptible to the fallacies of distributed computing, a series of misconceptions that can lead to significant issues in software development and deployment.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] Finding the right balance in the number of events can be quite difficult.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] Generating too many detailed events can overwhelm the system, making it hard to analyze the overall event flow effectively.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] This challenge becomes even greater when rollbacks are required.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] Conversely, if events are overly consolidated, it can lead to unnecessary processing and responses from event consumers.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] To achieve an optimal balance, Mark Richards recommends to consider the impact of each event and whether consumers need to review the event payloads to determine their actions.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] For instance, in a compliance check scenario, it may be adequate to publish just two types of events: compliant and non-compliant.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] This method ensures that each event is only processed by the relevant consumers, reducing unnecessary workload.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] One of the challenges of using event driven architecture is error handling.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] One way to address this issue is to use a separate error-handler processor.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] So, when the event consumer experiences an error, it immediately and asynchronously sends the erroneous event to the error-handler processor and moves on.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] Error-handler processor tries to fix the error and sends the event back to the original channel.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] But if the error-handler processor fails, then it can send the erroneous event to an administrator for further inspection.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] Note that if you use an error-handler processor, erroneous events will be processed out of sequence when they are resubmitted.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] Another challenge of using event driven architecture is data loss.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] If any of the components crashes before successfully processing and handing over the event to its next component, then the event is dropped and never makes it into the final destination.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] To minimize the chance of data loss, you can persist in-transit events and remove / dequeue the events only when the next component has acknowledged the receipt of the event.
[src:webhooks-pattern/event-driven-architecture] These features are usually known as "client acknowledge mode" and "last participant support".
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] HTTP is a request–response protocol in the client–server model.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] A transaction starts with a client submitting a request to the server, the server attempts to satisfy the request and returns a response to the client that describes the disposition of the request and optionally contains a requested resource such as an HTML document or other content.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] In a common scenario, a web browser acts as the client, and a web server, hosting one or more websites, is the server.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] A web browser is an example of a user agent (UA).
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] Other types of user agent include the indexing software used by search providers (web crawlers), voice browsers, mobile apps, and other software that accesses, consumes, or displays web content.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] HTTP is designed to permit intermediate network elements to improve or enable communications between clients and servers.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] High-traffic websites often benefit from web cache servers that deliver content on behalf of upstream servers to improve response time.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] Web browsers cache previously accessed web resources and reuse them, whenever possible, to reduce network traffic.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] HTTP proxy servers at private network boundaries can facilitate communication for clients without a globally routable address, by relaying messages with external servers.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] To allow intermediate HTTP nodes (proxy servers, web caches, etc.) to accomplish their functions, some of the HTTP headers (found in HTTP requests/responses) are managed hop-by-hop whereas other HTTP headers are managed end-to-end (managed only by the source client and by the target web server).
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] A web resource is located by a uniform resource locator (URL), using the Uniform Resource Identifier (URI) schemes *http* and *https*.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] URIs are encoded as hyperlinks in HTML documents, so as to form interlinked hypertext documents.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] The protocol has been revised over time.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] A version is identified as HTTP/# where # is the version number.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] This article covers aspects of all versions but provides primary coverage for HTTP/0.9, HTTP/1.0, and HTTP/1.1.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] Separate articles cover HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 in detail.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] In HTTP/1.0, a separate TCP connection to the same server is made for every resource request.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] In HTTP/1.1, instead a TCP connection can be reused to make multiple resource requests (i.e. of HTML pages, frames, images, scripts, stylesheets, etc.).
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] HTTP/1.1 communications therefore experience less latency as the establishment of TCP connections presents considerable overhead, especially under high traffic conditions.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] Enhancements added with HTTP/2 allow for less latency and, in most cases, higher speeds than HTTP/1.1 communications.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] HTTP/3 uses QUIC + UDP transport protocols instead of TCP.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] Only the IP layer is used (which UDP, like TCP, builds on).
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] This slightly improves the average speed of communications and avoids the occasional problem of TCP connection congestion that can temporarily block or slow down the data flow of all its streams (another form of "*head of line blocking*").
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] HTTP/2 is supported by 71% of websites (34.1% HTTP/2 + 36.9% HTTP/3 with backwards compatibility) and supported by almost all web browsers (over 98% of users).
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] It is also supported by major web servers over Transport Layer Security (TLS) using an Application-Layer Protocol Negotiation (ALPN) extension where TLS 1.2 or newer is required.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] HTTP/3 is used on 36.9% of websites and is supported by most web browsers, i.e.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] (at least partially) supported by 97% of users.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] HTTP/3 uses QUIC instead of TCP for the underlying transport protocol.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] Like HTTP/2, it does not obsolete previous major versions of the protocol.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] In 2019, support for HTTP/3 was first added to Cloudflare and Chrome and also enabled in Firefox.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] HTTP/3 has lower latency for real-world web pages and loads faster than HTTP/2, in some cases over three times faster than HTTP/1.1, which is still commonly the only protocol enabled.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] HTTPS, the secure variant of HTTP, is used by more than 85% of websites.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] HTTP presumes an underlying and reliable transport layer protocol.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] The standard choice of the underlying protocol prior to HTTP/3 is Transmission Control Protocol (TCP).
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] HTTP/3 uses a different transport layer called QUIC, which provides reliability on top of the unreliable User Datagram Protocol (UDP).
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] HTTP/1.1 and earlier have been adapted to be used over plain unreliable UDP in multicast and unicast situations, forming HTTPMU and HTTPU.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] They are used in UPnP and Simple Service Discovery Protocol (SSDP), two protocols usually run on a local area network.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] HTTP is a stateless application-level protocol and it requires a reliable network transport connection to exchange data between client and server.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] In HTTP implementations, TCP/IP connections are used using well-known ports (typically port 80 if the connection is unencrypted or port 443 if the connection is encrypted, see also List of TCP and UDP port numbers).
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] In HTTP/2, a TCP/IP connection plus multiple protocol channels are used.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] In HTTP/3, the application transport protocol QUIC over UDP is used.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] Data is exchanged through a sequence of request–response messages which are exchanged by a session layer transport connection.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] An HTTP client initially tries to establish a connection, real or virtual, with a server.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] An HTTP server listening on the port accepts the connection and then waits for a client's request message.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] The client sends its HTTP request message.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] Upon receiving the request the server sends back an HTTP response message, which includes header(s) plus a body if it is required.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] The body of this response message is typically the requested resource, although an error message or other information may also be returned.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] At any time and for many reasons, either the client or server can close the connection.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] Closing a connection is usually advertised by one or more HTTP headers in the last request or response.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] In HTTP/0.9, the TCP/IP connection is always closed after server response has been sent, so it is never persistent.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] In HTTP/1.0, the TCP/IP connection should always be closed by server after a response has been sent.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] In HTTP/1.1, a keep-alive-mechanism was officially introduced so that a connection could be reused for more than one request/response.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] Such persistent connections reduce request latency perceptibly because the client does not need to re-negotiate the TCP 3-Way-Handshake connection after the first request has been sent.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] Another positive side effect is that, in general, the connection becomes faster with time due to TCP's slow-start-mechanism.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] HTTP/1.1 added also HTTP pipelining in order to further reduce lag time when using persistent connections by allowing clients to send multiple requests before waiting for each response.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] Because of this, only HEAD and some GET requests (i.e. limited to real file requests and so with URLs without query string used as a command, etc.) could be pipelined in a safe and idempotent mode.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] After many years of struggling with the problems introduced by enabling pipelining, this feature was first disabled and then removed from most browsers.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] Pipelining was also removed because of the announced adoption of HTTP/2.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] HTTP/2 extended the usage of persistent connections by multiplexing many concurrent requests/responses through a single TCP/IP connection.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] HTTP/3 does not use TCP/IP connections but QUIC + UDP.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] In HTTP/0.9, a requested resource was always sent in its entirety.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] HTTP/1.0 added headers to manage resources cached by a client in order to allow conditional GET requests.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] As a stateless protocol, HTTP does not require the web server to retain information or status about each user for the duration of multiple requests.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] If a web application needs an application session, it implements it via HTTP cookies, hidden variables in a web form or another mechanism.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] Typically, to start a session, an interactive login is performed, and to end a session, a logout is requested by the user.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] These kind of operations use a custom authentication mechanism, not HTTP authentication.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] HTTP provides multiple authentication schemes such as basic access authentication and digest access authentication which operate via a challenge–response mechanism whereby the server identifies and issues a challenge before serving the requested content.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] HTTP provides a general framework for access control and authentication, via an extensible set of challenge–response authentication schemes, which can be used by a server to challenge a client request and by a client to provide authentication information.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] The authentication mechanisms described above belong to the HTTP protocol and are managed by client and server HTTP software (if configured to require authentication before allowing client access to one or more web resources), and not by the web applications using an application session.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] The HTTP authentication specification includes realms that provide an arbitrary, implementation-specific construct for further dividing resources common to a given root URI.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] The realm value string, if present, is combined with the canonical root URI to form the protection space component of the challenge.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] This in effect allows the server to define separate authentication scopes under one root URI.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] The most popular way of establishing an encrypted HTTP connection is HTTPS.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] Two other methods for establishing an encrypted HTTP connection also exist: Secure Hypertext Transfer Protocol, and using the HTTP/1.1 Upgrade header to specify an upgrade to TLS.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] Browser support for these two is, however, nearly non-existent.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] This section describes messages for HTTP/1.1.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] Later versions, HTTP/2 and HTTP/3, use a binary protocol, where headers are encoded in a single `HEADERS` and zero or more `CONTINUATION` frames using HPACK (HTTP/2) or QPACK (HTTP/3), which both provide efficient header compression.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] The request or response line from HTTP/1 has also been replaced by several pseudo-header fields, each beginning with a colon (`:`).
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] At the highest level, a message consists of a header followed by a body.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] A header consists of lines of ASCII text; each terminated with a carriage return and line feed sequence.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] Structured data that differs for request vs. response.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] lines (at least 1 for HTTP/1.1); see below.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] A body consists of data in any format; not limited to ASCII.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] The format must match that specified by the `Content-Type` header field if the message contains one.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] A body is optional or, in other words, can be blank.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] Before HTTP/2, the term *entity* was used to mean the body plus header fields that describe the body.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] In particular, not all headers were considered part of the entity.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] The term *entity header* referred to a header that was considered part of the entity, and sometimes the body was called the *entity body*.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] Modern documentation uses *body* and *header* without using *entity*.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] A header field represents metadata about the containing message.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] Generally, the information of a header field is used by software and not shown to the user.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] A header field line is formatted as a name-value pair with a colon separator.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] Whitespace is not allowed around the name, but leading and trailing whitespace is ignored for the value part.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] Unlike a method name that must match exactly (case-sensitive), a header field name is matched ignoring case although often shown with each word capitalized.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] For example, the following are header fields for `Host` and `Accept-Language`.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] The standards do not limit the size of a header field or the number of fields in a message.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] However, most servers, clients, and proxy software impose limits for practical and security reasons.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] For example, the Apache 2.3 server by default limits the size of each field to 8190 bytes, and there can be at most 100 header fields in a single request.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] Although deprecated by RFC 7230, in the past, long lines could be split into multiple lines with a continuation line starting with a space or tab character.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] A request is sent by a client to a server.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] The start line includes a method name, a request URI and the protocol version with a single space between each field.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] Request header fields allow the client to pass additional information beyond the request line, acting as request modifiers (similarly to the parameters of a procedure).
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] They give information about the client, about the target resource, or about the expected handling of the request.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] In the HTTP/1.1 protocol, all header fields except `Host` are optional.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] A request line containing only the path name is accepted by servers to maintain compatibility with HTTP clients before the HTTP/1.0 specification in RFC 1945.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] The protocol structures transaction as operating on resources.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] What a resource represents, whether pre-existing data or data that is generated dynamically, depends on the implementation of the server.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] Often, the resource corresponds to a file or the output of an executable running on the server.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] A request identifies a method (sometimes informally called *verb*) to classify the desired action to be performed on a resource.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] The HTTP/1.0 specification defined the GET, HEAD, and POST methods as well as listing the PUT, DELETE, LINK and UNLINK methods under additional methods.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] However, the HTTP/1.1 specification added five new methods: PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, OPTIONS, and TRACE.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] Any client can use any method and the server can be configured to support any combination of methods.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] If a method is unknown to an intermediate, it will be treated as an unsafe and non-idempotent method.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] There is no limit to the number of methods that can be defined, which allows for future methods to be specified without breaking existing infrastructure.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] For example, WebDAV defined seven new methods and RFC 5789 specified the PATCH method.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] A general-purpose web server is required to implement at least GET and HEAD, and all other methods are considered optional by the specification.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] This is in contrast to HTTP header field names which are case-insensitive.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] The request is for a representation of a resource.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] include the representation data in the body.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] in the response header, without having to transfer the entire representation.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] The request is to process a resource in some way.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] The request is to create or update a resource with the state in the request.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] A distinction from POST is that the client specifies the target location on the server.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] to the origin server identified by the request target.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] Request is for a report of the HTTP methods that are supported for a resource.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] This can be used to check the functionality of a web server by requesting '*' instead of a specific resource.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] Requests the server to respond with the received request in the response body.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] That way a client can see what (if any) changes or additions have been made by intermediaries.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] The request is to modify a resource according to its partial state in the request.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] Compared to PUT, this can save bandwidth by sending only part of a resource's representation instead of all of it.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] A request method is *safe* if a request with that method has no intended effect on the server.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] The methods GET, HEAD, OPTIONS, and TRACE are defined as safe.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] In other words, safe methods are intended to be read-only.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] Safe methods can still have side effects not seen by the client, such as appending request information to a log file or charging an advertising account.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] In contrast, the methods POST, PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, and PATCH are not safe.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] They may modify the state of the server or have other effects such as sending an email.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] Such methods are therefore not usually used by conforming web robots or web crawlers; some that do not conform tend to make requests without regard to context or consequences.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] Despite the prescribed safety of GET requests, in practice their handling by the server is not technically limited in any way.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] Careless or deliberately irregular programming can allow GET requests to cause non-trivial changes on the server.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] This is discouraged because of the problems which can occur when web caching, search engines, and other automated agents make unintended changes on the server.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] For example, a website might allow deletion of a resource through a URL such as *https://example.com/article/1234/delete*, which, if arbitrarily fetched, even using GET, would simply delete the article.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] A properly coded website would require a DELETE or POST method for this action, which non-malicious bots would not make.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] One example of this occurring in practice was during the short-lived Google Web Accelerator beta, which prefetched arbitrary URLs on the page a user was viewing, causing records to be automatically altered or deleted *en masse*.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] The beta was suspended only weeks after its first release, following widespread criticism.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] A request method is *idempotent* if multiple identical requests with that method have the same effect as a single such request.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] The methods PUT and DELETE, and safe methods are defined as idempotent.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] Safe methods are trivially idempotent, since they are intended to have no effect on the server whatsoever; the PUT and DELETE methods, meanwhile, are idempotent since successive identical requests will be ignored.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] A website might, for instance, set up a PUT endpoint to modify a user's recorded email address.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] If this endpoint is configured correctly, any requests which ask to change a user's email address to the same email address which is already recorded—e.g. duplicate requests following a successful request—will have no effect.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] Similarly, a request to DELETE a certain user will have no effect if that user has already been deleted.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] In contrast, the methods POST, CONNECT, and PATCH are not necessarily idempotent, and therefore sending an identical POST request multiple times may further modify the state of the server or have further effects, such as sending multiple emails.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] In some cases this is the desired effect, but in other cases it may occur accidentally.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] A user might, for example, inadvertently send multiple POST requests by clicking a button again if they were not given clear feedback that the first click was being processed.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] While web browsers may show alert dialog boxes to warn users in some cases where reloading a page may re-submit a POST request, it is generally up to the web application to handle cases where a POST request should not be submitted more than once.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] Note that whether or not a method is idempotent is not enforced by the protocol or web server.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] It is perfectly possible to write a web application in which (for example) a database insert or other non-idempotent action is triggered by a GET or other request.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] To do so against recommendations, however, may result in undesirable consequences, if a user agent assumes that repeating the same request is safe when it is not.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] A request method is *cacheable* if responses to requests with that method may be stored for future reuse.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] The methods GET, HEAD, and POST are defined as cacheable.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] In contrast, the methods PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, OPTIONS, TRACE, and PATCH are not cacheable.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] A response is sent to the client by the server.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] The start line of a response consists of the protocol version, a status code and optionally a reason phrase with fields separated by a single space character.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] The following response start line specifies protocol version `HTTP/1.1`, status code `400` and reason phrase `Bad Request`.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] Response header fields allow the server to pass additional information beyond the status line, acting as response modifiers.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] They give information about the server or about further access to the target resource or related resources.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] Each response header field has a defined meaning which can be further refined by the semantics of the request method or response status code.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] The status code is a three-digit, decimal, integer value that represents the disposition of the server's attempt to satisfy the client's request.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] Generally, a client handles a response primarily based on the status code and secondarily on response header fields.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] A client may not understand each status code that a server reports but it must understand the class as indicated by the first digit and treat an unrecognized code as equivalent to the x00 code of that class.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] The request was received, continuing process.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] The request was successfully received, understood, and accepted.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] Further action needs to be taken in order to complete the request.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] The request cannot be fulfilled due to an issue that the client might be able to control.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] The server failed to fulfill an apparently valid request.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] The standard reason phrases are only recommendations.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] A web server is allowed to use a localized equivalent.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] If a status code indicates a problem, the user agent might display the reason phrase to the user to provide further information about the nature of the problem.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] The standard also allows the user agent to attempt to interpret the reason phrase, though this might be unwise since the standard explicitly specifies that status codes are machine-readable and reason phrases are human-readable.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] The following demonstrates an HTTP/1.1 request-response transaction for a server at www.example.com, port 80.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] HTTP/1.0 would use the same messages except for a few missing headers.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 would use the same request-response mechanism but with different representations for HTTP headers.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] The following is a request with no body.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] It consists of a start line, 6 header fields and a blank line – each terminated with a carriage return and line feed sequence.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] The `Host` header field distinguishes between various DNS names sharing a single IP address, allowing name-based virtual hosting.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] While optional in HTTP/1.0, it is mandatory in HTTP/1.1.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] Although not clear in the representation above (due to limitations of this wiki), the blank line at the end results in ending in two line terminator sequences.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] Represented as a stream of characters, a shorted version of above shows this more clearly with `<CRLF>` representing a line terminator sequence: `GET / HTTP/1.1<CRLF>Host: www.example.com<CRLF><CRLF>`.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] In the following response, the ETag (entity tag) header field is used to determine if a cached version of the requested resource is identical to the current version of the resource on the server.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] The `Content-Type` header field specifies the Internet media type of the data conveyed by the HTTP message, and `Content-Length` indicates its length in bytes.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] The HTTP/1.1 webserver publishes its ability to respond to requests for a byte range of the resource by including `Accept-Ranges: bytes`.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] This is useful, if the client needs to have only certain portions of a resource sent by the server, which is called byte serving.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] When `Connection: close` is sent, it means that the web server will close the TCP connection immediately after the end of the transfer of this response.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] Most of the header fields are optional but some are mandatory.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] When header `Content-Length` is missing from a response with a body, then this should be considered an error in HTTP/1.0 but it may not be an error in HTTP/1.1 if header `Transfer-Encoding: chunked` is present.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] Chunked transfer encoding uses a chunk size of 0 to mark the end of the content.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] Some old implementations of HTTP/1.0 omitted the header `Content-Length` when the length of the body was not known at the beginning of the response and so the transfer of data to client continued until server closed the socket.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] `Content-Encoding: gzip` informs the client that the body is compressed per the gzip algorithm.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] A content delivery protocol that was displaced by HTTP in the early 1990s.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] A Gopher-inspired protocol which mandates privacy-related features.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] Tim Berners-Lee and his team at CERN are credited with inventing HTTP, along with HTML and the associated technology for a web server and a client user interface called web browser.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] Berners-Lee designed HTTP in order to help with the adoption of his other idea: the "WorldWideWeb" project, which was first proposed in 1989, now known as the World Wide Web.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] Development of HTTP was initiated in 1989 and summarized in a simple document describing the behavior of a client and a server using the first HTTP version, named 0.9.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] That version was subsequently developed, eventually becoming the public 1.0.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] Development of early HTTP Request for Comments (RFC) documents started a few years later in a coordinated effort by the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) and the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C), with work later moving to the IETF.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] The protocol used had only one method, namely GET, which would request a page from a server.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] The response from the server was always an HTML page.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] Since 1992, a new document was written to specify the evolution of the basic protocol towards its next full version.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] It supported both the simple request method of the 0.9 version and the full GET request that included the client HTTP version.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] This was the first of the many unofficial HTTP/1.0 drafts that preceded the final work on HTTP/1.0.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] The HTTP WG planned to revise and publish new versions of the protocol as HTTP/1.0 and HTTP/1.1 within 1995, but, because of the many revisions, that timeline lasted much more than one year.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] The HTTP WG planned also to specify a far future version of HTTP called HTTP-NG (HTTP Next Generation) that would have solved all remaining problems, of previous versions, related to performances, low latency responses, etc. but this work started only a few years later and it was never completed.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] In May 1996, RFC 1945 was published as a final HTTP/1.0 revision of what had been used in previous 4 years as a pre-standard HTTP/1.0-draft which was already used by many web browsers and web servers.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] In early 1996 developers started to even include unofficial extensions of the HTTP/1.0 protocol (i.e. keep-alive connections, etc.) into their products by using drafts of the upcoming HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] Since early 1996, major web browsers and web server developers also started to implement new features specified by pre-standard HTTP/1.1 drafts specifications.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] End-user adoption of the new versions of browsers and servers was rapid.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] In March 1996, one web hosting company reported that over 40% of browsers in use on the Internet used the new HTTP/1.1 header "Host" to enable virtual hosting, and that by June 1996, 65% of all browsers accessing their servers were pre-standard HTTP/1.1 compliant.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] In January 1997, RFC 2068 was officially released as HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] In June 1999, RFC 2616 was released to include all improvements and updates based on previous (obsolete) HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] Resuming the old 1995 plan of previous HTTP Working Group, in 1997 an *HTTP-NG Working Group* was formed to develop a new HTTP protocol named HTTP-NG (HTTP New Generation).
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] A few proposals / drafts were produced for the new protocol to use multiplexing of HTTP transactions inside a single TCP/IP connection, but in 1999, the group stopped its activity passing the technical problems to IETF.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] In 2007, the IETF HTTP Working Group (HTTP WG bis or HTTPbis) was restarted firstly to revise and clarify previous HTTP/1.1 specifications and secondly to write and refine future HTTP/2 specifications (named httpbis).
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] In 2009, Google announced SPDY – a binary protocol they developed to speed up web traffic between browsers and servers.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] In many tests, using SPDY was indeed faster than using HTTP/1.1.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] SPDY was integrated into Google's Chromium and then into other major web browsers.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] Some of the ideas about multiplexing HTTP streams over a single TCP connection were taken from various sources, including the work of W3C HTTP-NG Working Group.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] In 2012, HTTP Working Group (HTTPbis) announced the need for a new protocol; initially considering aspects of SPDY and eventually deciding to derive the new protocol from SPDY.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] In May 2015, HTTP/2 was published as RFC 7540.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] The protocol was quickly adopted by web browsers already supporting SPDY and more slowly by web servers.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] As of 2022, HTTP/0.9 support has not been officially, completely deprecated and is still present in many web servers and browsers (for server responses only), even if usually disabled.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] It is unclear how long it will take to decommission HTTP/0.9.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] In 2020, the first drafts of HTTP/3 were published and major web browsers and web servers started to adopt it.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] On 6 June 2022, IETF standardized HTTP/3 as RFC 9114.
[src:webhooks-pattern/http] In June 2022, RFC documents were published that deprecated many of the previous documents and introducing a few minor changes and a refactoring of HTTP semantics description into a separate document.
[src:webhooks-pattern/publish-subscribe-pattern] In software architecture, the **publish–subscribe pattern** (**pub/sub**) is a messaging pattern in which message senders, called **publishers**, categorize messages into classes (or *topics*), and send them without needing to know which components will receive them.
[src:webhooks-pattern/publish-subscribe-pattern] Message recipients, called **subscribers**, express interest in one or more classes and only receive messages in those classes, without needing to know the identity of the publishers.
[src:webhooks-pattern/publish-subscribe-pattern] This pattern decouples the components that produce messages from those that consume them, and supports asynchronous, many-to-many communication.
[src:webhooks-pattern/publish-subscribe-pattern] The publish–subscribe model is commonly contrasted with message queue-based and point-to-point messaging models, where producers send messages directly to consumers.
[src:webhooks-pattern/publish-subscribe-pattern] Publish–subscribe is a sibling of the message queue paradigm, and is typically a component of larger message-oriented middleware systems.
[src:webhooks-pattern/publish-subscribe-pattern] Many modern messaging frameworks and protocols, such as the Java Message Service (JMS), Apache Kafka, and MQTT, support both the pub/sub and queue-based models.
[src:webhooks-pattern/publish-subscribe-pattern] This pattern provides greater network scalability and supports more dynamic topologies, but can make it harder to modify the publisher’s logic or the structure of the published data.
[src:webhooks-pattern/publish-subscribe-pattern] Compared to synchronous patterns like RPC and point-to-point messaging, publish–subscribe provides the highest level of decoupling among architectural components.
[src:webhooks-pattern/publish-subscribe-pattern] However, it can also lead to semantic or format coupling between publishers and subscribers, which may cause systems to become entangled or brittle over time.
[src:webhooks-pattern/publish-subscribe-pattern] In publish–subscribe systems, subscribers typically receive only a subset of messages.
[src:webhooks-pattern/publish-subscribe-pattern] In most pub/sub systems, publishers and subscribers communicate through a central intermediary such as a message broker or event bus.
[src:webhooks-pattern/publish-subscribe-pattern] The broker receives messages from publishers and forwards them to the appropriate subscribers, optionally performing store and forward, priority queuing, or other routing logic.
[src:webhooks-pattern/publish-subscribe-pattern] Some pub/sub systems use **brokerless** architectures, in which publishers and subscribers discover each other and exchange messages directly.
[src:webhooks-pattern/publish-subscribe-pattern] For example, the Data Distribution Service (DDS) middleware uses IP multicast and metadata sharing to establish communication paths.
[src:webhooks-pattern/publish-subscribe-pattern] Brokerless systems require construction of overlay networks, often using Small-World topologies to enable efficient routing.
[src:webhooks-pattern/publish-subscribe-pattern] It was shown by Jon Kleinberg that efficient decentralized routing requires Navigable Small-World topologies, which are employed in federated or peer-to-peer pub/sub systems.
[src:webhooks-pattern/publish-subscribe-pattern] Locality-aware pub/sub networks use low-latency links to reduce message propagation time.
[src:webhooks-pattern/publish-subscribe-pattern] One of the earliest publicly described pub/sub systems was the "news" subsystem of the Isis Toolkit, presented at the 1987 ACM Symposium on Operating Systems Principles (SOSP '87).
[src:webhooks-pattern/publish-subscribe-pattern] As distributed systems became more common, the publish–subscribe model evolved to emphasize asynchronous messaging and broker-mediated communication, setting it apart from the more tightly coupled observer pattern.
[src:webhooks-pattern/publish-subscribe-pattern] Publishers are loosely coupled to subscribers, and need not even know of their existence.
[src:webhooks-pattern/publish-subscribe-pattern] With the topic being the focus, publishers and subscribers are allowed to remain ignorant of system topology.
[src:webhooks-pattern/publish-subscribe-pattern] Each can continue to operate as per normal independently of the other.
[src:webhooks-pattern/publish-subscribe-pattern] In the traditional tightly coupled client–server paradigm, the client cannot post messages to the server while the server process is not running, nor can the server receive messages unless the client is running.
[src:webhooks-pattern/publish-subscribe-pattern] Many pub/sub systems decouple not only the locations of the publishers and subscribers but also decouple them temporally.
[src:webhooks-pattern/publish-subscribe-pattern] A common strategy used by middleware analysts with such pub/sub systems is to take down a publisher to allow the subscriber to work through the backlog (a form of bandwidth throttling).
[src:webhooks-pattern/publish-subscribe-pattern] Pub/sub provides the opportunity for better scalability than traditional client-server, through parallel operation, message caching, tree-based or network-based routing, etc.
[src:webhooks-pattern/publish-subscribe-pattern] Outside of the enterprise environment, on the other hand, the pub/sub paradigm has proven its scalability to volumes far beyond those of a single data center, providing Internet-wide distributed messaging through web syndication protocols such as RSS and Atom.
[src:webhooks-pattern/publish-subscribe-pattern] These syndication protocols accept higher latency and lack of delivery guarantees in exchange for the ability for even a low-end web server to syndicate messages to (potentially) millions of separate subscriber nodes.
[src:webhooks-pattern/publish-subscribe-pattern] Redundant subscribers in a pub/sub system can help assure message delivery with minimal additional complexity.
[src:webhooks-pattern/publish-subscribe-pattern] For example, a factory may utilize a pub/sub system where equipment can publish problems or failures to a subscriber that displays and logs those problems.
[src:webhooks-pattern/publish-subscribe-pattern] If the logger fails (crashes), equipment problem publishers won't necessarily receive notice of the logger failure, and error messages will not be displayed or recorded by any equipment on the pub/sub system.
[src:webhooks-pattern/publish-subscribe-pattern] In a client/server system, when an error logger fails, the system will receive an indication of the error logger (server) failure.
[src:webhooks-pattern/publish-subscribe-pattern] However, the client/server system will have to deal with that failure by having redundant logging servers online, or by dynamically spawning fallback logging servers.
[src:webhooks-pattern/publish-subscribe-pattern] This adds complexity to the client and server designs, as well as to the client/server architecture as a whole.
[src:webhooks-pattern/publish-subscribe-pattern] In a pub/sub system, redundant logging subscribers that are exact duplicates of the existing logger can be added to the system to increase logging reliability without any impact to any other equipment on the system.
[src:webhooks-pattern/publish-subscribe-pattern] The feature of assured error message logging can also be added incrementally, subsequent to implementing the basic functionality of equipment problem message logging.
[src:webhooks-pattern/publish-subscribe-pattern] The most serious problems with pub/sub systems are a side-effect of their main advantage: the decoupling of publisher from subscriber.
[src:webhooks-pattern/publish-subscribe-pattern] A pub/sub system must be designed carefully to be able to provide stronger system properties that a particular application might require, such as assured delivery.
[src:webhooks-pattern/publish-subscribe-pattern] The pub/sub pattern scales well for small networks with a small number of publisher and subscriber nodes and low message volume.
[src:webhooks-pattern/publish-subscribe-pattern] However, as the number of nodes and messages grows, the likelihood of instabilities increases, limiting the maximum scalability of a pub/sub network.
[src:webhooks-pattern/publish-subscribe-pattern] For pub/sub systems that use brokers (servers), the argument for a broker to send messages to a subscriber is in-band, and can be subject to security problems.
[src:webhooks-pattern/publish-subscribe-pattern] Brokers might be fooled into sending notifications to the wrong client, amplifying denial of service requests against the client.
[src:webhooks-pattern/publish-subscribe-pattern] Brokers themselves could be overloaded as they allocate resources to track created subscriptions.
[src:webhooks-pattern/publish-subscribe-pattern] Even with systems that do not rely on brokers, a subscriber might be able to receive data that it is not authorized to receive.
[src:webhooks-pattern/publish-subscribe-pattern] An unauthorized publisher may be able to introduce incorrect or damaging messages into the pub/sub system.
[src:webhooks-pattern/publish-subscribe-pattern] This is especially true with systems that broadcast or multicast their messages.
[src:webhooks-pattern/publish-subscribe-pattern] Transport Layer Security (SSL/TLS)) can prevent unauthorized access, but cannot prevent damaging messages from being introduced by authorized publishers.
[src:webhooks-pattern/publish-subscribe-pattern] Architectures other than pub/sub, such as client/server systems, are also vulnerable to authorized message senders that behave maliciously.
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] In push technology, clients can express their preferences for certain types of information or data, typically through a process known as the publish–subscribe model.
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] In this model, a client "subscribes" to specific information channels hosted by a server.
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] When new content becomes available on these channels, the server automatically sends, or "pushes," this information to the subscribed client.
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] Under certain conditions, such as restrictive security policies that block incoming HTTP requests, push technology is sometimes simulated using a technique called polling.
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] In these cases, the client periodically checks with the server to see if new information is available, rather than receiving automatic updates.
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] Synchronous conferencing and instant messaging are examples of push services.
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] Chat messages and sometimes files are pushed to the user as soon as they are received by the messaging service.
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] Both decentralized peer-to-peer programs (such as WASTE) and centralized programs (such as IRC or XMPP) allow pushing files, which means the sender initiates the data transfer rather than the recipient.
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] Email may also be a push system: SMTP is a push protocol (see Push e-mail).
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] However, the last step—from mail server to desktop computer—typically uses a pull protocol like POP3 or IMAP.
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] Modern e-mail clients make this step seem instantaneous by repeatedly polling the mail server, frequently checking it for new mail.
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] The IMAP protocol includes the IDLE command, which allows the server to tell the client when new messages arrive.
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] The original BlackBerry was the first popular example of push-email in a wireless context.
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] Another example is the PointCast Network, which was widely covered in the 1990s.
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] It delivered news and stock market data as a screensaver.
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] Both Netscape and Microsoft integrated push technology through the Channel Definition Format (CDF) into their software at the height of the browser wars, but it was never very popular.
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] Other uses of push-enabled web applications include software updates distribution ("push updates"), market data distribution (stock tickers), online chat/messaging systems (webchat), auctions, online betting and gaming, sport results, monitoring consoles, and sensor network monitoring.
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] The Web push proposal of the Internet Engineering Task Force is a simple protocol using HTTP version 2 to deliver real-time events, such as incoming calls or messages, which can be delivered (or "pushed") in a timely fashion.
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] The protocol consolidates all real-time events into a single session which ensures more efficient use of network and radio resources.
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] A single service consolidates all events, distributing those events to applications as they arrive.
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] This requires just one session, avoiding duplicated overhead costs.
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] Web Notifications are part of the W3C standard and define an API for end-user notifications.
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] A notification allows alerting the user of an event, such as the delivery of an email, outside the context of a web page.
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] As part of this standard, Push API is fully implemented in Chrome, Firefox, and Edge, and partially implemented in Safari as of February 2023.
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] HTTP server push (also known as HTTP streaming) is a mechanism for sending unsolicited (asynchronous) data from a web server to a web browser.
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] HTTP server push can be achieved through any of several mechanisms.
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] As a part of HTML5 the Web Socket API allows a web server and client to communicate over a full-duplex TCP connection.
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] Generally, the web server does not terminate a connection after response data has been served to a client.
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] The web server leaves the connection open so that if an event occurs (for example, a change in internal data which needs to be reported to one or multiple clients), it can be sent out immediately; otherwise, the event would have to be queued until the client's next request is received.
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] Most web servers offer this functionality via CGI (e.g., Non-Parsed Headers scripts on Apache HTTP Server).
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] The underlying mechanism for this approach is chunked transfer encoding.
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] Another mechanism is related to a special MIME type called `multipart/x-mixed-replace`, which was introduced by Netscape in 1995.
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] Web browsers interpret this as a document that changes whenever the server pushes a new version to the client.
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] It is still supported by Firefox, Opera, and Safari today, but it is ignored by Internet Explorer and is only partially supported by Chrome.
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] It can be applied to HTML documents, and also for streaming images in webcam applications.
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] The WHATWG Web Applications 1.0 proposal includes a mechanism to push content to the client.
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] On September 1, 2006, the Opera web browser implemented this new experimental system in a feature called "Server-Sent Events".
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] In this technique, the server takes advantage of persistent HTTP connections, leaving the response perpetually "open" (i.e., the server never terminates the response), effectively fooling the browser to remain in "loading" mode after the initial page load could be considered complete.
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] The server then periodically sends snippets of JavaScript to update the content of the page, thereby achieving push capability.
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] By using this technique, the client doesn't need Java applets or other plug-ins in order to keep an open connection to the server; the client is automatically notified about new events, pushed by the server.
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] One serious drawback to this method, however, is the lack of control the server has over the browser timing out; a page refresh is always necessary if a timeout occurs on the browser end.
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] Long polling is itself not a true push; long polling is a variation of the traditional polling technique, but it allows emulating a push mechanism under circumstances where a real push is not possible, such as sites with security policies that require rejection of incoming HTTP requests.
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] With long polling, the client requests to get more information from the server exactly as in normal polling, but with the expectation that the server may not respond immediately.
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] If the server has no new information for the client when the poll is received, then instead of sending an empty response, the server holds the request open and waits for response information to become available.
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] Once it does have new information, the server immediately sends an HTTP response to the client, completing the open HTTP request.
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] Upon receipt of the server response, the client often immediately issues another server request.
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] In this way the usual response latency (the time between when the information first becomes available and the next client request) otherwise associated with polling clients is eliminated.
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] This technique, used by chat applications, makes use of the XML Socket object in a single-pixel Adobe Flash movie.
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] Under the control of JavaScript, the client establishes a TCP connection to a unidirectional relay on the server.
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] The relay server does not read anything from this socket; instead, it immediately sends the client a unique identifier.
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] Next, the client makes an HTTP request to the web server, including this identifier with it.
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] The web application can then push messages addressed to the client to a local interface of the relay server, which relays them over the Flash socket.
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] The advantage of this approach is that it appreciates the natural read-write asymmetry that is typical of many web applications, including chat, and as a consequence it offers high efficiency.
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] Since it does not accept data on outgoing sockets, the relay server does not need to poll outgoing TCP connections *at all*, making it possible to hold open tens of thousands of concurrent connections.
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] In this model, the limit to scale is the TCP stack of the underlying server operating system.
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] In services such as cloud computing, to increase reliability and availability of data, it is usually pushed (replicated) to several machines.
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] For example, the Hadoop Distributed File System (HDFS) makes 2 extra copies of any object stored.
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] RGDD focuses on efficiently casting an object from one location to many while saving bandwidth by sending minimal number of copies (only one in the best case) of the object over any link across the network.
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] For example, Datacast is a scheme for delivery to many nodes inside data centers that relies on regular and structured topologies and DCCast is a similar approach for delivery across data centers.
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] A push notification is a message that is "pushed" from a back-end server or application to a user interface, e.g. mobile applications or desktop applications.
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] Apple introduced push notifications for iPhone in 2009, and in 2010 Google released "Google Cloud to Device Messaging" (superseded by Google Cloud Messaging and then by Firebase Cloud Messaging).
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] Push notifications are mainly divided into two approaches, local notifications and remote notifications.
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] For local notifications, the application schedules the notification with the local device's OS.
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] The application sets a timer in the application itself, provided it is able to continuously run in the background.
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] When the event's scheduled time is reached, or the event's programmed condition is met, the message is displayed in the application's user interface.
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] Remote notifications are handled by a remote server.
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] Under this scenario, the client application needs to be registered on the server with a unique key (e.g., a UUID or Apple *Device Token*).
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] The server then transmits the message against the unique key to deliver it to the client via an agreed client/server protocol such as HTTP or XMPP.
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] When the push notification arrives at the client, it can cause the display of short notifications or messages, set badges on application icons, blink or continuously light up the notification LED, or play alert sounds to attract user's attention.
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] Push notifications are usually used by applications to bring information to users' attention.
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] Real-time push notifications may raise privacy issues since they can be used to bind virtual identities of social network pseudonyms to the real identities of the smartphone owners.
[src:webhooks-pattern/push-technology] The use of unnecessary push notifications for promotional purposes has been criticized as an example of attention theft.
[src:webhooks-pattern/web-api] A **web API** is an application programming interface (API) for either a web server or a web browser.
[src:webhooks-pattern/web-api] As a web development concept, it can be related to a web application's client side (including any web frameworks being used).
[src:webhooks-pattern/web-api] A server-side web API consists of one or more publicly exposed **endpoints** to a defined request–response message system, typically expressed in JSON or XML by means of an HTTP-based web server.
[src:webhooks-pattern/web-api] A server API (SAPI) is not considered a server-side web API, unless it is publicly accessible by a remote web application.
[src:webhooks-pattern/web-api] A client-side web API is a programmatic interface to extend functionality within a web browser or other HTTP client.
[src:webhooks-pattern/web-api] Originally these were most commonly in the form of native plug-in browser extensions however most newer ones target standardized JavaScript bindings.
[src:webhooks-pattern/web-api] The Mozilla Foundation created their WebAPI specification which is designed to help replace native mobile applications with HTML5 applications.
[src:webhooks-pattern/web-api] Google created their Native Client architecture which is designed to help replace insecure native plug-ins with secure native sandboxed extensions and applications.
[src:webhooks-pattern/web-api] They have also made this portable by employing a modified LLVM AOT compiler.
[src:webhooks-pattern/web-api] A server-side web API consists of one or more publicly exposed *endpoints* to a defined request–response message system, typically expressed in JSON or XML.
[src:webhooks-pattern/web-api] The web API is exposed most commonly by means of an HTTP-based web server.
[src:webhooks-pattern/web-api] Endpoints are important aspects of interacting with server-side web APIs, as they specify where resources can be accessed by third-party software.
[src:webhooks-pattern/web-api] Usually the access is via a URI to which HTTP requests are posted, and from which the response is thus expected.
[src:webhooks-pattern/web-api] Web APIs may be public or private, the latter of which requires an *access token*.
[src:webhooks-pattern/web-api] Endpoints need to be static, otherwise the correct functioning of software that interacts with them cannot be guaranteed.
[src:webhooks-pattern/web-api] If the location of a resource changes (and with it the endpoint) then previously written software will break, as the required resource can no longer be found at the same place.
[src:webhooks-pattern/web-api] As API providers still want to update their web APIs, many have introduced a versioning system in the URI that points to an endpoint.
[src:webhooks-pattern/web-api] Web 2.0 Web APIs often use machine-based interactions such as REST and SOAP.
[src:webhooks-pattern/web-api] RESTful web APIs use HTTP methods to access resources via URL-encoded parameters, and use JSON or XML to transmit data.
[src:webhooks-pattern/web-api] By contrast, SOAP protocols are standardized by the W3C and mandate the use of XML as the payload format, typically over HTTP.
[src:webhooks-pattern/web-api] Furthermore, SOAP-based Web APIs use XML validation to ensure structural message integrity, by leveraging the XML schemas provisioned with WSDL documents.
[src:webhooks-pattern/web-api] A WSDL document accurately defines the XML messages and transport bindings of a Web service.
[src:webhooks-pattern/web-api] Server-side web APIs are interfaces for the outside world to interact with the business logic.
[src:webhooks-pattern/web-api] For many companies this internal business logic and the intellectual property associated with it are what distinguishes them from other companies, and potentially what gives them a competitive edge.
[src:webhooks-pattern/web-api] They do not want this information to be exposed.
[src:webhooks-pattern/web-api] However, in order to provide a web API of high quality, there *needs* to be a sufficient level of documentation.
[src:webhooks-pattern/web-api] One API provider that not only provides documentation, but also links to it in its error messages is Twilio.
[src:webhooks-pattern/web-api] However, there are now directories of popular documented server-side web APIs.
[src:webhooks-pattern/web-api] The number of available web APIs has grown consistently over the past years, as businesses realize the growth opportunities associated with running an open platform, that any developer can interact with.
[src:webhooks-pattern/web-api] ProgrammableWeb tracks over 24000 Web APIs that were available in 2022, up from 105 in 2005.
[src:webhooks-pattern/web-api] There are few major software applications/services that do not offer some form of web API.
[src:webhooks-pattern/web-api] One of the most common forms of interacting with these web APIs is via embedding external resources, such as tweets, Facebook comments, YouTube videos, etc.
[src:webhooks-pattern/web-api] In fact there are very successful companies, such as Disqus, whose main service is to provide embeddable tools, such as a feature-rich comment system.
[src:webhooks-pattern/web-api] Any website of the TOP 100 Alexa Internet ranked websites uses APIs and/or provides its own APIs, which is a very distinct indicator for the prodigious scale and impact of web APIs as a whole.
[src:webhooks-pattern/web-api] As the number of available web APIs has grown, open source tools have been developed to provide more sophisticated search and discovery.
[src:webhooks-pattern/web-api] APIs.json provides a machine-readable description of an API and its operations, and the related project APIs.io offers a searchable public listing of APIs based on the APIs.json metadata format.
[src:webhooks-pattern/web-api] Many companies and organizations rely heavily on their Web API infrastructure to serve their core business clients.
[src:webhooks-pattern/web-api] In 2014 Netflix received around 5 billion API requests, most of them within their private API.
[src:webhooks-pattern/web-api] Many governments collect a lot of data, and some governments are now opening up access to this data.
[src:webhooks-pattern/web-api] The interfaces through which this data is typically made accessible are web APIs.
[src:webhooks-pattern/web-api] Web APIs allow for data, such as "budget, public works, crime, legal, and other agency data" to be accessed by any developer in a convenient manner.
[src:webhooks-pattern/web-api] An example of a popular web API is the Astronomy Picture of the Day API operated by the American space agency NASA.
[src:webhooks-pattern/web-api] It is a server-side API used to retrieve photographs of space or other images of interest to astronomers, and metadata about the images.
[src:webhooks-pattern/web-api] The documentation states that this endpoint accepts GET requests.
[src:webhooks-pattern/web-api] It requires one piece of information from the user, an API key, and accepts several other optional pieces of information.
[src:webhooks-pattern/web-api] Such pieces of information are known as *parameters*.
[src:webhooks-pattern/web-api] The parameters for this API are written in a format known as a query string, which is separated by a question mark character (`?`) from the endpoint.
[src:webhooks-pattern/web-api] An ampersand (`&`) separates the parameters in the query string from each other.
[src:webhooks-pattern/web-api] Together, the endpoint and the query string form a URL that determines how the API will respond.
[src:webhooks-pattern/web-api] This URL is also known as a *query* or an *API call*.
[src:webhooks-pattern/web-api] In the below example, two parameters are transmitted (or *passed*) to the API via the query string.
[src:webhooks-pattern/web-api] The first is the required API key and the second is an optional parameter — the date of the photograph requested.
[src:webhooks-pattern/web-api] Visiting the above URL in a web browser will initiate a GET request, calling the API and showing the user a result, known as a *return value* or as a *return*.
[src:webhooks-pattern/web-api] This API returns JSON, a type of data format intended to be understood by computers, but which is somewhat easy for a human to read as well.
[src:webhooks-pattern/web-api] The above API return has been reformatted so that names of JSON data items, known as *keys*, appear at the start of each line.
[src:webhooks-pattern/web-api] Although this API can be called by an end user with a web browser (as in this example) it is intended to be called automatically by software or by computer programmers while writing software.
[src:webhooks-pattern/web-api] JSON is intended to be parsed by a computer program, which would extract the URL of the photograph and the other metadata.
[src:webhooks-pattern/web-api] The resulting photo could be embedded in a website, automatically sent via text message, or used for any other purpose envisioned by a software developer.
[src:webhooks-pattern/webhook] In web development, a **webhook** is a method of augmenting or altering the behavior of a web page or web application with custom callbacks.
[src:webhooks-pattern/webhook] These callbacks may be maintained, modified, and managed by third-party users who need not be affiliated with the originating website or application.
[src:webhooks-pattern/webhook] In 2007, Jeff Lindsay coined the term *webhook* from the computer programming term *hook*.
[src:webhooks-pattern/webhook] Webhooks are "user-defined HTTP callbacks".
[src:webhooks-pattern/webhook] They are usually triggered by some event, such as pushing code to a repository, a purchase, a comment being posted to a blog and many more use cases.
[src:webhooks-pattern/webhook] When that event occurs, the source site makes an HTTP request to the URL configured for the webhook.
[src:webhooks-pattern/webhook] Users can configure them to cause events on one site to invoke behavior on another.
[src:webhooks-pattern/webhook] Common uses are to trigger builds with continuous integration systems or to notify bug tracking systems.
[src:webhooks-pattern/webhook] Because webhooks use HTTP, they can be integrated into web services without adding new infrastructure.
[src:webhooks-pattern/webhook] When the client (the originating website or application) makes a webhook call to the third-party user's server, the incoming POST request should be authenticated to avoid a spoofing attack and its timestamp verified to avoid a replay attack.
[src:webhooks-pattern/webhook] The sender may choose to keep a constant list of IP addresses from which requests will be sent.
[src:webhooks-pattern/webhook] This is not a sufficient security measure on its own, but it is useful for when the receiving endpoint is behind a firewall or NAT.
